    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2087482638" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2087482638" />
    <a title="InkedBookDragon" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/68953824-inkedbookdragon"><img alt="InkedBookDragon" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1506880857p2/68953824.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2087482638?book_show_action=true">Aug 10, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="InkedBookDragon" class="user" itemprop="url" name="InkedBookDragon" href="/user/show/68953824-inkedbookdragon">InkedBookDragon</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780547028644" href="/book/show/3137945-wait-till-helen-comes">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2087482638" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2196862723105056572">I am reviewing Wait Till Helen Comes: A Ghost Story by Mary Downing Hahn. It is written more towards children in grades 5-7. I stumbled upon this book and thought that I would give it a shot. It looked interesting. What did I have to lose?<br/><br/>I was pleasantly surprised with this one. It may have been written for the younger crowd but it doesn&apos;t always feel that way. It deals with very serious issues such as adapting to blended families, severe guilt, communication, fear of abandonment, and forgivene</span>
  <span id="freeText2196862723105056572" style="display:none">I am reviewing Wait Till Helen Comes: A Ghost Story by Mary Downing Hahn. It is written more towards children in grades 5-7. I stumbled upon this book and thought that I would give it a shot. It looked interesting. What did I have to lose?<br /><br />I was pleasantly surprised with this one. It may have been written for the younger crowd but it doesn't always feel that way. It deals with very serious issues such as adapting to blended families, severe guilt, communication, fear of abandonment, and forgiveness. Add in the ghost of a child hellbent on finding a new playmate and you have a creepy read.<br /><br />I find myself intrigued by this author. The style of this book was quite refreshing. I wonder if her other works leave the reader with the great sense of contentment that I experienced with this book. Yes, it read like a book written for children but it felt like more. It was full of moments that left me shuddering a little. Hahn definitely has this grasp on the human mind and fear.<br /><br />I am giving this book the rating of four stars because it did feel rushed. Hahn wanted to get as much story in there as possible which is tricky for a book of this length (192 pages). She is definitely a true master of the ghost story. Overall, very enjoyable read.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="2196862723105056572" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


